beer_brewer_name: Hair of the Dog Brewing Company
review_blob: I really dont have words to describe what is here.  Thanks to Allen for all his work and his generosity sharing this beautiful brew.
Just what the doctor ordered after spending most of the day on my a$$ learning how to snowboard.  Reminded me of a bock on steroids.  Hoping to run into the barleywine on the next trip.
beer_name: Mt. Hood Pittock Wee Heavy Scotch Ale

review_blob: Dark tan head, very dark.  A little bit sweet, good roasted flavor.  The food was great too.
beer_name: Big Horse Nightmare Russian Imperial Stout

review_blob: Very dark.  Pours with a good solid head you'd expext from a belgian, starting brownish and finishing more cream colored.  Spicy, and slightly more carbonated than I expected.  The end of the 750 was better than the beginning...showing the benefits of warmth and breath.  Excellent.

I was given the advice to save this beer for 5 yeras or so...but being the impatient person that I am, I decided this 2001 bottle was good to go.  Poured nice and virtually head free, which wasn't unexpected from what I read on the label.  Very very big beer, lots of malts of course, but you could taste the complexities beginning to come out.  It mellowed some as I let it breathe...but I'd really like to see this beer in 3 or 4 more years.   Mmmm.

Have you ever eaten a snowcone, and focused on using your spoon more than your straw?  So that at the end of the cone, you've depleted the ice, whilst there's still a whole lot of syrup left?  Apply that concept to an otherwise balanced beer....and welcome to blarney time.

beer_brewer_name: Portland Brewing Company (Pyramid - North American Breweries)
review_blob: Poured in my favoreite b-wine glass, a traditional english pint glass.  When it was poured, I was at first disappointed that the color was more orange than red, but that disappointment quickly gave way to enjoyment as I tested the aroma and took a  taste.  Delightful blend of malt and hops, a little sweet a little spicy.  Very good.
Pours with rich amber color, head abounding with lace.  Strong fruity aroma gives way to a spicy finish.

Mmmm....Imperial Stout.  I'm assuming this is the Russian Imperial Stout I had at the pub.  They put it on their XS-line...because of the high alcohol content blah blah blah.  Pretty good stout, nice dark color with a dark brown head.  Well balanced, more hops than the average stout, and a decent amount of kick.  Nice.

Had this guy in a nice little visit to the brewery in Newport.  If you ask me, this is what I'll look for in the future out of a pilsner.  It has the basic pilsner flavor, yet this one actually has a back bone.  Very smooth, hides the alcohol.  Probably good it\'s one of those pub only brews (except for the cool limited edition bottles, but i'm not sure how far out those get), because this is the kind of beer that could sneak up on someone.

Had this been on tap, in Newport, at the brewery.  Pretty sweet place worth checking out.  Looked like your average amber ale, yet hit with a blind side of hops I wasn't expecting, and had a nice subtle alcohol finish.  Pretty decent stuff.

This beer is no Westy 12.  But I don't read anywhere where it claims to be.  Since we disrespect the malt liquor style, much like we do the american standard light, these beers will never be rated in comparison to their kind, instead they will be compared to the westy 12's out there.  And that's probably good, this beer doesn't have much going for it.  Except that it's probably the best of its kind.  Its hard to argue with 8.1%, 40oz for $1.50.  Just realize that a 7oz foghorn goes for $3.00.  With similar alcohol percentages, foghorn is approximately 11X more expensive than this.  My recommendation for this beer is to put down a 750 of Stone Ruination IPA by yourself....and since you won't taste anything else for about a week, slam these guys in the process.  That's the poor college student in me thinking.  Since there's no value column, we'll incorporate that into the overall.

So, I've just moved to Vancouver, WA, in the Portland, OR area.  My stuff all got delivered yesterday, yet I didn't get to pack very much.  So today when it was time to try Unibroue 11, I opened up one of the 4 large boxes of beer glasses I own, and picked the one that was on top.  After unwrapping the opaque wrapper, I revealed a New Belgium goblet.  Satisfied that the glass would suffice, I left the rest of the box for later.  A couple untwists of wire and a cork pop later, my glass was full.  I held the glass up to my computer screen to see the typical belgium style cloudy golden appearence.  A brief wiff revealed those typical belgian banana-y yeasty aromas, and I was ready to dive in.  A good solid gulp revealed those typical belgium flavors, maybe a little more banana-y than I'm used to.  Much like anos196....i mean andrew196...I was surprised that I didn't taste the 11% that the bottle claimed.  So, since I couldn't taste the ABV, I decided to make sure I finished the bottle in the same 30 minutes I had finished the 10 the year before...and see how the ALKIEHOL affected me.  This beer is definitely higher than 8%, but like everyone else I'm skeptical of the 11%, but it sure sounds fancy on the bottle.  Maybe if you let it rest for 11 more years... who knows.  Good beer.

This beer is basically their regular stout aged in whiskey barrels.  I think it adds a delightful hint of sweetness that helps balance the beer overall.  Wonderful black color and dark head.  Starts and finishes well.

split a bottle with andrew196 on my recent journey back to texas.  i have this beer halfway in between foghorn and hog heaven.  i think 196's problems with it stem from the bars we closed down before our tasting.  great beer, some time in the cellar could make it even better.

I don't know about everyone else, but there are times when I go out, and I'm just not in the mood for beer.  If I'm in a chilling mood, I'll probably sip some scotch, but if it's party time...bring on the rum and cokes (thanks to living in the caribbean for a while).  Normally the first drink you order is pretty average, then after a nice tip, they continue to get stronger and stronger.  It seems like as long as you can taste...the 50/50 mix works best (or if you're andrew196, and you've just split a growler of 10%abv happy jacks with nstal, you start pouring nstal crown royal and cokes with a 90% crown/coke ratio).  This beer reminds me exactly of that, I've had my first drink and I've moved on to the 50/50 mix.  Be careful, 5 or 6 of these will totally mess up the average drinker.  Beautiful dark color, doesn't mess with any of that CO2 crap forming a head.  Aroma hints of a beer not near as strong as it is.  A hair too sweet to have more than 5 or 6, but quality all around.  DFH living a little outside of the box.

My eyes are closed, I'm deep in thought.  I walk into a bar named Touche's, for its someones birthday.  We order our flaming dr. peppers, and the bar tender pulls out 9 glasses.  He proceeds to fill 8 of them half full with some light macro beer.  he then places 8 shot glasses on the rims of each adjacent glass, and fills each shot glass with amaretto.  then a little bacardi 151 tops off the shots of amaretto.  just when things were interesting enough, he proceeds to fill his mouth with 151, spilling some onto his left hand.  a borrowed lighter ignites his hand into a vibrant blue flame, and he empties the contents of his mouth through the blue flame, creating a giant fireball which lights each of the 8 shot glasses on fire.  Tipping one of the end shot glasses, it falls into a beer, knocking the next shot glass into the following beer.  In less than a second, all 8 shots are swimming in the 8 beers.  Quickly the "flaming dr. peppers" are distributed amongst the group.  Bottoms up and the drink quickly disappears...with the final sip tasting of dr. pepper, hence the name.  Concentrate this experience into one sweet, almost syrupy beer, and you have this bourbon bock.

the little old lady at the bar (married to the brewmaster) described this beer as their "slut beer" because after 2 of them...that's how you act.  It was also described as their highest alcohol beer, and since they had a couple others in the 7's, i'm gonna estimate this one in the 8+ range.  This red beer was a beautiful amber, poured with a decent head in a traditional english pint glass.  the taste was enhanced by the home-ly-ness of the place, i felt like i was a visitor in their home.

Wow, a place with barleywine on tap the first day of june.  Pretty sweet.  First sip reminded me of foghorn, but it didn't hold up as well through the glass.  The restaurant here was pretty cool, you get to cool your own food at your table on a super-hot rock.  Very nice.
Pretty, cloudy, amber, quality white head.  Malty aromas.  Spicey flavor.

A true Old Ale, yes, and a very good one.  Malt & wood thing, fruity notes, herbal hops.  Reddish brown - quite dark and cloudy. Rich malty aroma - toffee, alcohol, and a bit of dark fruit in there as well.
beer_name: Fish Tale Old Woody English Old Ale

review_blob: "Wow, this is interesting," she said.  "You can definitely taste the Muscat."  Wait, we're talking about a beer here.  What's up with that?  Definitely a tasty beverage, beer?  barleywine? ale?  wine?  Who knows.  Nevertheless, this stuff's pretty good.
beer_name: Dogfish Head Midas Touch Golden Elixir

review_blob: This beer was good.  Better than a lot of B-wines I've had, but certainly not the best.  Good balance of sweet malts and bitter hops.  New to the Washington scene, a welcome addition.
beer_name: Flying Dog Horn Dog Barley Wine

review_blob: Poured this right next to a Lagunitas Gnarley Wine and they looked identical.  Tasted pretty similar too.

This beer was above expectations.  Poured absolutely perfectly, beautiful red color and bright white head, decent retention.  Smelled of fruit, malt, and definitely hops.  The hops came through a tad too strong, and this beer was slightly lacking in alcohol.  Those are my only complaints.
Pours dark red, very little head.  A little sweet, a little spicey.  6.2% is very very low for a barleywine.  Watery.  Not so good.
1996.  Dark red color, very little head.  syrupy aroma. Very very sweet.  Bottle 0991.  Pretty cool.

beer_brewer_name: North By Northwest Restaurant and Brewery
review_blob: I agree with andrew on this one, definitely a far cry from the other beers at this place, and a little weak on the barleywine scale.  Fortunately it is very drinkable.
You find that serves a bunch of average beer, benefits from being right next to a college, then you find this.  Fruity aroma, strong flavor (but not 11.5% strong).  Well balanced.  Awesome.
I moved to seattle a little late to find this guy on tap.  Unfortunately it seems they took the conservative route.  Decent brew, very mild.
I heard big things about this beer, then had it on tap once, and decided it wasn't too special after all.  Definitely very good, but not one of the best.
When life gives you lemons, make lemonade.  They surely did this.  They ended up with a darn good beer.  Very drinkable.
Had this guy after a 1200 mile drive.  Brewpub didn't have it on tap, only in bottles.  Very typical for a b-wine, nothing original.  Good overall.
had this on tap, very nice.  very very dark.  great abv.  malts definitely dominate this beer, but time to time that's good.
Pours beautifully, very smooth, very rich, very balanced.  Much like foghorn, enough quantity made to have some consistancy.  Yummy
2001.  Excellent brew, glad to know its from close to home.  Dark red, strong, sweet, balanced.  Very nice.
beer_name: Fish Tale Leviathan Barleywine - Barrel Aged

review_blob: I was quite unimpressed with this compared to most b-wines, but must applaud the effort.  Rich sweet aroma, lacks balance and complexity.
I would have a much better feeling about this beer if the place didn't also have foghorn on tap.  Nevertheless it's a great effort from a small brewpub.  A little fruity, very simple, easy drinking.
beer_name: Draught House Marleys Gnarly Barley Wine

review_blob: This to me is a barleywine/IPA mixture.  One of the few beers of this type that are dominated by hops.  Best served with chicken wings that have been marinated in hog heaven and fried in bacon drippings.

Had this beer at the end of an 800 mile drive, and then being lost for about an hour and a half in the bay area.  Looked pretty dark for a bwine, and the 70 IBU's were intimidating, but it was well balanced and turned out to be quite drinkable.

2002.  Pours more orange than red, nice translucent barleywine appearance.  Blessed with a rush of white head made up of tiny white bubbles, yet the life span is very short.  Aroma contains both hops and malts.  A little bit more bitter than I like, but age could take care of that.
UPDATED: MAR 30, 2003
1996, #7367.  Pours murky, dark, brown.  Head=0.  Very sweet aroma, very sweet.  Bottle boasts 9% ABV, I wouldn't doubt if that's increased some since '96.  Earns bonus points for the wine-like cork.

beer_brewer_name: Hair of the Dog Brewing Company
review_blob: Crazy amounts of head.  Bright golden color.  Firm alcohol taste.  Fruity aroma.  Hoppy finish.  Very nice.
UPDATED: JUL 30, 2003

beer_brewer_name: Hair of the Dog Brewing Company
review_blob: Very dark, very little head.  A hint of spice, a little sweet, rounded out with a little roasted flavor.  Very good.

The label on this bottle looks like the labels you can print out and put on CD's that you were too cheap to buy so you burned them on your computer.  Nice dark red color, and its amazing that i'm a few minutes into a barley wine and there's still bubbles from the head left.  Splendid balance of flavors, perfect amount of ABV, not hidden, yet not focused upon.  Quality brew.

Starts off with a cool looking old dude on the label.  No ABV listed.  Pours exactly like a foghorn, same color, same minimal head.  Aroma is weakened by the lack of carbonation, but no worries.  The first few sips had lots of roasted flavor for a b-wine, but those mellowed as the beer warmed.  Excellent brew.

Spicey, definitely spicey.  Certainly can feel the nutmeg in the beginning.  This is the 2001 vintage.  Aroma not near as bold as the taste.  Pours very dark, looks like syrup when it pours.  Wish I could get a good feel for the alcohol....I'd put it in the 8's ABV.  It gets better as it warms.  Very good, although I probably wouldn't kill for it....maybe mangle.

I just moved to the Seattle area about 3 weeks ago.  This stuff is brewed about 10 miles from my apartment.  It comes in a cool looking brown bottle with a painted on label and one of those pop tops that I first saw on a bottle of grolsch.  Deep red color.  Initially on the pour there was very little head and only a few very large bubbles, but then the CO2 came blasting through and formed a nice smooth 2" head.  Unfortunately it didn't last very long, but that's expected for the style.  The bottle boasts of "black currant character," and it's definitely there, almost too much at first.  But as the beer warms and mellows, the sweet malts help balance the flavor.  Reminds me of an alcoholic version of a black currant juice drink I had in London last summer.  BTW, this was from the 2000 batch.
